<TITLE> First hajj flight takes off </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 31 (bdnews24.com)  The first hajj flight left for Saudi city of Jeddah on Friday carrying 512 pilgrims. Chief adviser's special assistant in charge of civil aviation and tourism ministry Mahbub Jamil told bdnews24.com Fakhruddin Ahmed inaugurated the first hajj flight at Zia International Airport at 3:45pm. Special prayers were held before the pilgrims had left Dhaka. The chief adviser exchanged greetings with the hajj pilgrims. Religious affairs adviser AF Hassan Ariff was also present. Jamil said the flight will land at Jeddah hajj terminal. Bangladesh Biman will carry 28,561 of the 48,876 hajj pilgrims registered under government and private management to and from Dhaka. Saudi flag carrier Saudia will fly the rest of the pilgrims. "Houses have been rented for all pilgrims, both under government and private management, in Saudi Arabia. The government's administrative and medical teams have already reached there," hajj officer Md Bazlul Haq Biswas told bdnews24.com. This time the religious affairs ministry has arranged one guide for each group of 50 hajj pilgrims. "The order is being carried out in case of those under government management, as well. If the private hajj agencies violate the order legal action including cancellation of licence would be taken," Biswas said. bdne
